05905nam a22009375i 9780520968264DE-B159720210621102733.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210621t20192019cau    fo  d z      eng d  a2019002873  a97805209682647 a10.1525/97805209682642doi  a(DE-B1597)536434  a(OCoLC)1084619988  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA00aTP447.M4bW87 2019 4aTP447.M4bW87 2019 7aSOC0550002bisacsh04a664.9292231 aWurgaft, Benjamin Aldes, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMeat Planet :bArtificial Flesh and the Future of Food /cBenjamin Aldes Wurgaft. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (264 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCalifornia Studies in Food and Culture ;v6900tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- t1. Cyberspace/Meatspace -- t2. Meat -- t3. Promise -- t4. Fog -- t5. Doubt -- t6. Hope -- t7. Tree -- t8. Future -- t9. Prometheus -- t10. Memento -- t11. Copy -- t12. Philosophers -- t13. Maastricht -- t14. Kosher -- t15. Whale -- t16. Cannibals -- t17. Gathering/Parting -- t18. Epimetheus -- tNotes -- tSelected Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn 2013, a Dutch scientist unveiled the world's first laboratory-created hamburger. Since then, the idea of producing meat, not from live animals but from carefully cultured tissues, has spread like wildfire through the media. Meanwhile, cultured meat researchers race against population growth and climate change in an effort to make sustainable protein. Meat Planet explores the quest to generate meat in the lab-a substance sometimes called "cultured meat"-and asks what it means to imagine that this is the future of food.Neither an advocate nor a critic of cultured meat, Benjamin Aldes Wurgaft spent five years researching the phenomenon. In Meat Planet, he reveals how debates about lab-grown meat reach beyond debates about food, examining the links between appetite, growth, and capitalism. Could satiating the growing appetite for meat actually lead to our undoing? Are we simply using one technology to undo the damage caused by another? Like all problems in our food system, the meat problem is not merely a problem of production. It is intrinsically social and political, and it demands that we examine questions of justice and desirable modes of living in a shared and finite world. Benjamin Wurgaft tells a story that could utterly transform the way we think of animals, the way we relate to farmland, the way we use water, and the way we think about population and our fragile ecosystem's capacity to sustain life. He argues that even if cultured meat does not "succeed," it functions-much like science fiction-as a crucial mirror that we can hold up to our contemporary fleshy dysfunctions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 0aArtificial foods. 0aMeat industry and tradexMoral and ethical aspects. 0aMeat substitutes. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Agriculture & Food (see also POLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Agriculture & Food Policy).2bisacsh  aanimals.  acapitalism.  acultured meat.  afake meat.  afarmland.  afood system.  afragile ecosystem.  afuture of food.  agenerating meat in the lab.  agrowing appetite for meat.  ahamburger.  ajustice.  alab created meat.  alab grown.  amanufactured meat.  ameat.  aproduction.  asocial and political.  asustainable protein.  asustaining life.  avegan.  avegetarian.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishz978311061076508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019z9783110664232oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook packa